Introduction

-statement of problem/circumstance -significance of problem -purpose of study -assumptions and limitations -Review of preceding research and literature

This project aim is to understand the spread of COVID–19 and the reasons why the pandemic has emerged as a global matter of concern in a couple of months. Now that we have enough data to analyze what happened in this last two years, we want to show the gravity of COVID–19. To do so, we focused our interest on the United States.

Research questions

In this investigation, we set out to answer the following questions.

  1. How have the number of deaths due to COVID–19 in the United State evolved with time since the beginning of the pandemic ?

  2. Next, we investigate how COVID–19 deaths are distributed across some notable risk factors. In particular, we ask ourselves : How are deaths distributed across age groups ? How are deaths distributed across the recorded location of death (meaning type of institution or private residence) ?

  3. How has the mortality of COVID–19 evolved with time ?

  4. How are COVID–19 cases correlated across neighbouring states ?

  5. Can we predict the number of deaths in a given state and given month from the number of deaths in the k-th degree neighbour of that state ?

Approaches

To answer the above questions, we will proceed as follows : A descriptive and visual approach where we will produce interactive plots with information on the number of deaths along different dimensions : geographically, temporally and by different risk factors. We will then proceed with the analysis of mortality rate as a function of time and based on different risk factors. Afterwards we switch to the correlation and spatial comparison studies : between two selected states, two neighbouring states or considering different levels of neighbourhoods through a separation analysis.

Sources of information / datasets

In this project, several datasets were used to answer our questions. Each one of them refers to the same population (the US). Here are more specific descriptions.

US deaths within categories and states

The first dataset we use is about provisional COVID–19 deaths by place of death and age from the CDC in the US. A complete description of it is available on the web page.

The variables we used in this project are : Group, Year, Month, HHS Region, State, Place of Death, Age group, COVID-19 Deaths and Total Deaths. What is particular here is that the sum of COVID-19 Deaths is not the total number of deaths in the US. Actually, we need to filter our data by Group, State, Place of Death and Age Group in order to get what we want.

A last thing we should take into account is that those numbers of deaths are not the exact number that happened during a given period. The reason is that there is always a lag in time (usually 1 to 8 weeks) between the instant when the death occurred and between when the death certificate is completed and submitted for reporting purposes.

US deaths within categories and states

The second dataset we chose to use is about COVID–19 cases and deaths by state over time from the CDC in the US. This dataset contains the total number, probable and confirmed cases and deaths from COVID–19 from each state from the 22nd of January 2020 to the 15th of October 2021. The variables we used are : submission_date, state, new_cases and new_deaths. We wanted to focus on the number of new cases per day to compare them between the States. The reason why we chose a different dataset from above is because tracing the number of cases is more sensitive in catching the global trend of spread than tracing the number of new deaths. Also, the above dataset only has the number per month, whereas this has for each day which makes the comparison more accurate and precise.

Other datasets used

The third dataset we used is about the U.S. population in 2019 by State (extract) by the Census Bureau in the U.S. This dataset is used to normalize the number of cases and deaths : since each state has a different size of population, we used the percentage of cases out of the total population of the state to compare the numbers from different states. We assumed that the population did not differ from 2019 with a confidence interval of 90% or above (the population of the states showed a global increase of less than 10% during the last 10 years).

The fourth dataset is about new cases and deaths per months. This dataset was extracted by the second dataset, by subtracting the total cases and deaths for each last days of consecutive months. This dataset was made to be used in parallel with the first dataset, and to compute the mortality rate.

Spatial exploration of Covid deaths in the United States over time

In this subsection, we intend to visualize our data before starting different analyses. To do so, we display the number of deaths on the United States map shown in Figures (1), (2), (3) and (4). The plotted data represents the deaths per 1 million individuals, we standardise the data according to the population of each state.

Figure (1) represents deaths of people regardless of their age as of July 2020. Figure (2) represents the deaths of people of all ages in July. We notice the growth in the number of deaths : 300 out of 1 million people in Arizona at the peak in July with an average of 70.05 across the country. In December 2020, we note an increase in mortality to over 500 deaths per million inhabitants in Colorado and North Dakota, along with a countrywide average of 310.32.

Figure (3) shows the total number of deaths over the entire two-year period for individuals aged 0-17 years. The average number of deaths nationally is 0.62 per 1 million inhabitants with a maximum value of 3.07 in Arizona. Figure (4) shows the total number of deaths over the two years for persons over 85 years of age. The average death rate rises to 576.24 deaths per million population with a maximum of 1158.76 in Rhode Island and a minimum of 117.35 in Hawaii. The examples chosen in this section are rather extreme and are meant to better visualize the data and discover interesting trends or factors to analyse later in this project.

An interactive version is available under this link. You can select which map to display based on time period, age range and place of death.

Mortality rate through time

First we are going to plot the mortality rate and the incidence rate for the US through time to analyse their evolution. Secondly we are going to plot the proportion of deaths of COVID–19 called the case fatality ratio. This is important to measure the severity of COVID–19.

Let’s load the data :

df <- read_csv("../Data/case_per_month.csv")

First, we are going to remove the column States and sum the new cases and respectively, the new deaths, for each month to get the number of total death in the country by month :

df = df[,-c(2)]
df_us = df[,-c(4)] #delete state
df_us = df_us %>%
group_by(end_date, year, month) %>% summarise_at(vars(new_deaths_per_month,new_cases_per_month),sum) %>%
ungroup()

So now, we have the data for the US and not for each state. To compute the mortality rate, We are going to take the population of the country for each year. This means that we are going to neglect the fact that for each month, the population changes (so that we don’t introduce a new data set).

Now we can have a look to the data to check that our modifications worked :

Now that we have added the population of the country at each month, we are going to compute the mortality rate.

Note that the mortality rate is generally expressed by the “number of persons dead per 100,000 of the population, per period of time”, in order to allow comparisons between different populations and time periods. So, we decided to represent the mortality rate by the number of persons who died per 10,000 persons of the population.

We are ready to plot the mortality rate through time :

First, with the emergence of the Covid, we can see that the mortality rate increases quickly. We can note that in the beginning of 2021, there is a peak of the mortality rate which can coincide with hospital saturation. Afterwards, in June, July 2021, the rate is low. This can be explained by the weather. Now, let’s compare the mortality rate to the incidence rate. The incidence rate represents the number of persons affected by COVID–19.

We can notice that the evolution of the incidence rate is similar to the evolution of the mortality rate. The peak at the beginning of the year 2021 is also present here. It seems coherent since the incidence rate is correlated to the number of deaths. Let’s plot both evolution at the same time to compare them.

We can see that when we plot both, the mortality rate is very small compared to the incidence rate which is normal. This shows that COVID–19 has spread quickly during these two years having a lot more cases than deaths. Now, we are going to compute the proportion of deaths in the country. The problem is that we don’t know when a person who died at a certain month had COVID–19. There are no links between the data. So we are going to take an approximation of the proportion of deaths per month.

Finally, we can see that at the beginning of the spread, COVID–19 was a very mortal diseases. The peak reaches 27% : this mean that at a given time (February) more than one in four people dies of COVID–19. This information is false, in fact, the high peak can be explained by the fact that at the beginning of the pandemic, there weren’t a lot of people tested. Therefore the majority of people who got tested were very sick people and so it explains why there was a very big percentage of death. After this peak, we can see that the proportion of deaths is more or less constant as we expected. This shows that the peak present in the mortality rate is explained by the high number of confirmed cases.

Impact of geolocation on cases and deaths from COVID–19

Correlations depending of neighbourship

In this section, we want to validate the hypothesis that the location of the states have an impact on the number of cases and deaths from COVID–19. In order to prove it, we looked into the new number of cases and deaths from COVID–19 per day in each state, and compared between them to see if neighbouring states had a more similar trend.

Below are the plots of two example states that are not neighbouring from each other, New York and California: the percentages of new COVID–19 cases over the total state population in New York and California are plotted as a function of time.

Figure(11)

Below are the plots of two example states that are neighbouring from each other, Nevada and California. We can observe that compared to the previous graph, the plots seem to look more alike.

Figure(12)

To check on different pairs of states, an interactive plot was made (Link). We can choose the pair with the two dropdowns at the top, and the states are named with its acronyms. Also, there are two modes, Cases and Deaths at the top left, which shows the plot of new cases and new deaths from COVID–19 respectively. Once the pair is chosen, the title will reveal if the two states are actually neighbours or not.

To verify the hypothesis, we computed the Pearson correlation coefficient for each pair of States. By taking the mean of the coefficients for pairs that are neighbours and the ones for the pairs that are not neighbours, we could see a big difference (0.7575626038139122 v.s. 0.5900159155676525) We can therefore say that the trends of new COVID–19 cases are similar if the states are neighbouring from each other. We could draw a similar conclusion for the number of deaths from COVID–19, although it is not as apparent as the number of cases. (0.4804464631622195 v.s. 0.34860163565334673)

Below are the box plots of Pearson correlation coefficients between the numbers of cases from two States when they are neighbours and when they are not.

Figure(13)

We can indeed observe that the Pearson correlation coefficient is significantly higher when the two States are neighbouring than when they are not.

Below are the box plots of Pearson correlation coefficients between the numbers of deaths from two States when they are neighbours and when they are not.

Figure(14)

The contrast for the number of new deaths is not a apparent as the number of new cases, but we can still retrieve the result we expected.

In conclusion, the location of the State indeed has an impact on the number of cases and deaths from COVID–19. We could observe that two states have a more similar trend when they are neighbours than when they are not. There were several waves of infection in different places, and we could observe a lagging peak in cases of farther states. The reason behind this phenomenon is because people would often move from one state to another closer state. For instance, we could expect that some people living in Nevada could go to California for work, and the disease might have spread along this movement of population. However, there can also be as many people moving to big farther cities as the ones moving to nearby cities, and in that case the trend can be similar even though the states are not neighbouring to each other. For instance, New York and California both have a peak in January, although they are situated on the both extremities of the country. This phenomenon might have occurred because those two states include the two biggest city in the U.S. – Los Angeles and New York City – and the migration of population between the two cities might have been frequent at that moment.

Predicting deaths from k-th degree neighbors

In this section, we propose and implement a linear model to predict the number of monthly COVID–19 deaths in a given state as a function of the number of deaths during the same month in a k-th degree neighbour of that state. Two states X and Y are k-th degree neighbours if at least k interstate borders must be crossed to go from one state to the other.

\[ E[N_X\mid N_Y] = b_0^{(k_{XY})}+ b_1^{(k_{XY})} N_Y \] For example, the above model can be used to predict the number of COVID–19 deaths in Massachusetts during a month given the number of deaths in Vermont during the same month, where Vermont and Massachusetts share a border and are thus 1st degree neighbours (\(k=1\)). The panel of figures below contains scatterplots of \(N_X\) against \(N_Y\) for any month and any two states that are neighbours of degree \(d\). In order to find the degree of neighbourship between two states, we have treated the states as nodes on a graph, where edges correspond to borders between states. We constructed an adjacency matrix between states sharing a border, and subsequently we used the Floyd–Warshall algorithm to find the smallest number of interstate borders connecting any two states. In each panel, we have indicated the parameters \(b_0\), \(b_1\) and the correlation coefficient \(\rho\) between \(N_X\) and \(N_Y\).

Next, we have plotted how the parameters \(b_0\), \(b_1\) and \(\rho\) vary as a function of degree of separation \(d\) below :

As expected, the predictive power of a neighbour decreases with increasing degree of the neighbour. We see that the variation in the number of deaths is large, and thus it is (unsurprisingly) hard to make accurate predictions of the number of deaths. The speed of attenuation of response \(b_1\) with \(d\) nonetheless sheds light on the spatial scale of the correlations between the number of deaths.

Discussion and conclusion

In this project, we have aimed to descriptively characterize the extent of COVID-19 deaths in the US during the global pandemic. We began by visualizing a dynamic heatmap in which we noticed a wave of increasing deaths from the south to the north of the US between July (307 deaths/million in Arizona,~253 deaths/million in Texas, ~245 deaths/million in Florida VS North Dakota ~40 deaths/million,Wisconsin 28deaths/million , Maine 18deaths/million) and December 2020(441 deaths/million in Arizona,~275 deaths/million in Texas, ~155 deaths/million in Florida VS North Dakota ~461 deaths/million,Wisconsin 306 deaths/million , Maine 153 deaths/million) : US map plots(develop more). As expected, we found that older individuals are overrepresented in the mortality statistics. Most people dying from Covid are older than 50-60 years. We also noticed periods of time with a substantial increase in mortality amongst infected individuals, which might be explained by a of shortage of available intensive care facilities in hospitals: Many Hospitals With No Beds Left Are Forced To Send COVID Patients To Cities Far Away ). Next, we observed that the correlation in number of deaths and cases of infection was greater for neighboring states than for states that are further away from each other. Based on this observation, we constructed a linear model to predict the number of deaths in a given state from the number of deaths in a k-th degree neighbor. As expected, the predictive power of the model decreased with the increasing degree of separation of the states. The predictions were most accurate in regimes with a low number of deaths. Overall, the findings cast light on the magnitude of deaths and distribution of deaths across key factors during the COVID-19 pandemic in the US.

Future improvements

As a further improvement and extension of the research, we suggest incorporating a forecasting model and visually displaying it in the same manner. We can also extend the following study and add more parameters such as health restrictions imposed by the government and their impact on the spread and deaths. We can further add the availability of hospitals as a parameter. With interesting and conclusive results, we can broaden our study to other countries or even other epidemics. Furthermore, another dimension to consider would be the vaccination: does it have a positive or negative effect on mortality? Finally, comorbidity can be considered.
